          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Old Havana (UNESCO 1982), founded in 1519, packs nearly a thousand historically significant buildings into just 5 km². Wander the Plaza de la Catedral — a baroque cathedral dating to 1777 with mismatched asymmetrical towers — then stroll the 460-metre pedestrian artery of Calle Obispo before reaching Plaza de Armas, where the Palacio de los Capitanes Generales (1776) still has its original wooden cobblestones, laid to muffle the sound of carriages and spare the governor his sleep.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 90
            },
            {
              "text": "El Capitolio (1926–1929), 207 metres long, shelters a 25-carat diamond beneath its 92-metre dome — the official kilometre zero of every road in Cuba. Its bronze Statue of the Republic (14.6 m tall, 30 tonnes) was the third-largest indoor statue in the world when it was unveiled.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Arrival and transfer from the airport area (about 30 minutes). As the day winds down, head straight to the Malecón for your first taste of Havana: a 8-km sea-front promenade built between 1901 and 1958, nicknamed 'the world's longest sofa.' At 9 pm, don't miss the cañonazo — a cannon fired nightly from the La Cabaña fortress across the bay.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 60
            }
