          "visits": [
            {
              "text": "Las Terrazas is a 1,000-person eco-village founded in 1968 out of an extraordinary act of ecological repair: after centuries of deforestation caused by coffee plantations and charcoal production, seven million trees — mahogany, cedar, teak — were replanted across 5,000 hectares of hillside terraces carved by hand (hence the name). In 1985, the Sierra del Rosario was designated Cuba's first UNESCO Biosphere Reserve. Today the community, built around an artificial lake, earns 60% of its income from eco-tourism.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 60
            },
            {
              "text": "Cafetal Buenavista is the ruin of a coffee plantation founded in the early 19th century by French colonists who fled the Haitian Revolution. The stone drying terraces, slave quarters and manor house still stand. At the region's peak, there were 54 plantations like this one — Buenavista is among the oldest survivors.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            },
            {
              "text": "The Orchid Garden at Soroa, 20 km from Las Terrazas, was created in the 1940s by a Canarian lawyer in memory of his wife and daughter. Spread across 35,000 m² of mountain terraces, it brings together over 700 orchid species — including 250 endemic to Cuba.",
              "place_id": "",
              "visit_duration_min": 45
            }
          ],
          "activities": [
            {
              "text": "Swim in the Baños del Río San Juan — a series of natural pools and small waterfalls deep in the tropical forest, 3 km from Las Terrazas. Cool, clear freshwater flows between moss-covered rocks.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 90,
              "practical_info": {
                "duration": "~1h30"
              }
            },
            {
              "text": "Guided hike through the Sierra del Rosario: over 120 bird species live here, including the tocororo — Cuba's national bird, wearing the red, white and blue of the Cuban flag — and the tiny, jewel-bright Cuban tody, a red-and-green endemic found nowhere else on earth.",
              "place_id": "",
              "activity_duration_min": 120,
              "practical_info": {
                "distance": "3 to 7 km depending on trail",
                "duration": "~2h",
                "difficulty": "Easy to moderate",
                "booking": "Guide required — book at Hotel Moka"
